Title : 1948 in British music
Text : {{1940s in music (UK)}}

This is a summary of '''1948 in music''' in the [[United Kingdom]].

==Events==
*[[16 January]] – The day after her New York concert debut, [[Kathleen Ferrier]] writes to her sister: "Some of the critics are enthusiastic, others unimpressed".<ref>Fifield, Christopher (ed.) (2003). Letters and Diaries of Kathleen Ferrier. Woodbridge, Suffolk: The Boydell Press. {{ISBN|1-84383-012-4}}. p.&nbsp;49</ref> 
*[[17 April]] – The death of Alice, [[Ivor Guest, 1st Viscount Wimborne#Family|Viscountess Wimborne]], lover of [[William Walton]], ends their 14-year affair.
*[[5 June]] – Opening of the first [[Aldeburgh Festival]], founded by [[Benjamin Britten]], [[Eric Crozier]] and [[Peter Pears]].
*[[13 October]] – [[Kathleen Ferrier]] joins Sir [[John Barbirolli]] and the [[Hallé Orchestra]] in a broadcast performance of Mahler's song cycle ''[[Kindertotenlieder]]''.
*October – The [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Duke of Edinburgh]] is introduced to musical comedy star [[Pat Kirkwood (actress)|Pat Kirkwood]] in her dressing room after a show.  They are seen together at a restaurant, creating a scandal in the newspapers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Edge |first=Simon |url=http://www.express.co.uk/features/view/29605/The-prince-and-the-showgirl |title=The prince and the showgirl &#124; Express Yourself &#124; &#124; Daily Express |publisher=Express.co.uk |date=2007-12-27 |accessdate=2014-06-07}}</ref>
*[[13 October]] – [[William Walton]] marries Susana Gil Passo.<ref>{{cite book|author=Friedrich Blume|title=Die Musik in Geschichte und Gegenwart: allgemeine Enzyklopädie der Musik|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_okYAAAAIAAJ|year=1968|publisher=Bärenreiter-Verlag|language=de}}</ref>
*''date unknown'' 
**[[Steuart Wilson]] becomes head of music at the BBC; the appointment results in the retirement of Sir [[Adrian Boult]] as chief conductor of the BBC Symphony Orchestra.<ref>Kennedy, Michael (1987). Adrian Boult. London: Hamish Hamilton. {{ISBN|0-333-48752-4}}. p215</ref>
**[[Harman Grisewood]] replaces [[George Barnes (BBC)|George Barnes]] as controller of the [[BBC Third Programme]].
**The National School of Opera is founded by [[Joan Cross]].<ref>D. Brook, Singers of Today (Revised Edition – Rockliff, London 1958), 55–60.</ref>

==Popular music==
*[[Anne Shelton (singer)|Anne Shelton]] – "[[If You Ever Fall in Love Again]]" ([[Dick Farrelly]])
*[[Dorothy Squires]] – "[[A Tree in the Meadow]]" ([[Billy Reid (British songwriter)|Billy Reid]])

==Classical music: new works==
*[[Malcolm Arnold]] – ''The Smoke'' (Overture), Op. 21
*[[Arnold Bax]] – ''Magnificat''<ref>{{cite book|author1=Maggie Humphreys|author2=Robert Evans|title=Dictionary of Composers for the Church in Great Britain and Ireland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WSLUAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA25|date=1 January 1997|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=978-0-7201-2330-2|pages=25}}</ref>
*[[Benjamin Britten]] – ''[[Saint Nicolas (Britten)|Saint Nicolas]]'', for tenor soloist, children's chorus, chorus, and orchestra<ref>{{cite book|author=Eric Walter White|title=Benjamin Britten, His Life and Operas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WUPPVlD7UnwC&pg=PA63|year=1983|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-04894-2|pages=63}}</ref>
*[[Michael Tippett]] – ''Suite in D for the Birthday of Prince Charles''<ref>{{cite book|author1=Michael Kennedy|author2=Tim Rutherford-Johnson|author3=Joyce Kennedy|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XX2sAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA857|date=15 August 2013|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-957854-2|pages=857}}</ref>
*[[Ralph Vaughan Williams]] – Partita for Double String Orchestra<ref>{{cite book|author=Ryan Ross|title=Ralph Vaughan Williams: A Research and Information Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FazDCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA294|date=17 March 2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-64616-7|pages=294}}</ref>

==Opera==
*[[Arthur Bliss]] – ''The Olympians''<ref>{{cite book|author=Stewart R. Craggs|title=Arthur Bliss: a source book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RIQYAQAAIAAJ|year=1996|publisher=Scolar Press|isbn=978-0-85967-940-4}}</ref>
*[[Norman Demuth]] – ''Le Flambeau''<ref>{{cite book|title=Enciclopedia dello spettacolo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZFUNAQAAMAAJ|year=1975|publisher=Unedi-Unione editoriale}}</ref>

==Film and Incidental music==
*[[William Alwyn]] – ''[[The Fallen Idol (film)|The Fallen Idol]]'' directed by [[Carol Reed]], starring [[Ralph Richardson]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Adrian Wright|title=The Innumerable Dance: The Life and Work of William Alwyn|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hg8WAxFjyrAC&pg=PA3|year=2008|publisher=Boydell & Brewer Ltd|isbn=978-1-84383-412-0|pages=3}}</ref>
*[[Arnold Bax]] – ''[[Oliver Twist (1948 film)|Oliver Twist]]'' directed by [[David Lean]], starring [[Alec Guinness]].
*[[Brian Easdale]] – ''[[The Red Shoes (1948 film)|The Red Shoes]]'' directed and produced by [[Michael Powell]] and [[Emeric Pressburger]].
*[[Constant Lambert]] – ''[[Anna Karenina (1948 film)|Anna Karenina]]'', starring [[Vivien Leigh]] and [[Ralph Richardson]].
*[[Elisabeth Lutyens]] – ''[[Penny and the Pownall Case]]'' (the first feature film to be scored by a female British composer).
*[[Ralph Vaughan Williams]] – ''[[Scott of the Antarctic (film)|Scott of the Antarctic]]'', starring [[John Mills]].
*[[William Walton]] – ''[[Hamlet (1948 film)|Hamlet]]'', directed by and starring [[Laurence Olivier]].
*[[John Wooldridge]] – ''[[The Guinea Pig (film)|The Guinea Pig]]'', starring [[Richard Attenborough]].

==Musical theatre==
*[[10 March]] – ''Carissima'', starring [[Ginger Rogers]] and [[David Hughes (tenor)|David Hughes]], opens at the [[Palace Theatre, London|Palace Theatre]] and runs for 488 performances.
*[[22 December]] – ''[[High Button Shoes]]'' ([[Jule Styne]] and [[Sammy Cahn]]) opens at the [[London Hippodrome|Hippodrome]] and runs for 291 performances.

==Musical films==
*''[[A Date with a Dream]]'', starring [[Terry-Thomas]], [[Jeannie Carson]] and [[Wally Patch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/11358 |title=BFI &#124; Film & TV Database &#124; DATE WITH A DREAM (1948) |publisher=Ftvdb.bfi.org.uk |date=2009-04-16 |accessdate=2012-02-12}}</ref>
*''[[Bless 'Em All (film)|Bless 'Em All]]'', starring [[Max Bygraves]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://old.bfi.org.uk/nationalarchive/news/mostwanted/bless-em-all.html |title=Bless 'Em All / BFI Most Wanted |publisher=British Film Institute |accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref> 
*''[[One Night with You (1948 film)|One Night with You]]'', directed by [[Terence Young (director)|Terence Young]] and starring [[Nino Martini]], [[Patricia Roc]] and [[Bonar Colleano]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/45080 |title=BFI &#124; Film & TV Database &#124; ONE NIGHT WITH YOU (1948) |publisher=Ftvdb.bfi.org.uk |date=2009-04-16 |accessdate=2014-06-07}}</ref>

==Births==
*[[17 January]] – [[Mick Taylor]], guitarist 
*[[19 January]] – [[Amanda Holden (writer)|Amanda Holden]], English playwright, lyricist and composer
*[[29 January]] – [[Mel Pritchard]], drummer (died [[2004 in British music|2004]])
*[[3 February]] – [[Gavin Henderson]], English trumpet player and conductor
*[[28 February]] – [[Geoff Nicholls]], keyboardist ([[Black Sabbath]] (died [[2017 in British music|2017]])
*[[4 March]] – [[Chris Squire]], guitarist, singer and songwriter
*[[22 March]] – [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]], composer
*[[16 April]] – [[Robert Kirby]], arranger (died [[2009 in British music|2009]])<ref>{{cite web|last=Irwin|first=Colin|title=Robert Kirby obituary|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/oct/07/robert-kirby-obituary|publisher=guardian.co.uk|accessdate=19 May 2011|date=7 October 2009}}</ref> 
*[[28 April]] – [[Scott Fitzgerald (singer)|Scott Fitzgerald]] (William McPhail), singer
*[[12 May]] – [[Steve Winwood]], R&B singer 
*[[15 May]] – [[Brian Eno]], synthesizer virtuoso and composer
*[[21 May]] – [[Leo Sayer]], singer-songwriter
*[[29 May]] – [[Michael Berkeley]], composer
*[[6 June]] – [[Richard Sinclair]], bass player ([[Caravan (band)|Caravan]], [[The Wilde Flowers]], [[Camel (band)|Camel]], and [[Hatfield and the North]])
*[[1 July]] – [[John Ford (musician)|John Ford]], English-American singer, songwriter and guitarist ([[Strawbs]], [[The Monks (UK band)|The Monks]], and [[Elmer Gantry's Velvet Opera]])
*[[4 July]] – [[Jeremy Spencer]], English guitarist ([[Fleetwood Mac]])
*[[5 July]] – [[Alan Hazeldine]], pianist and conductor (died [[2008 in British music|2008]])
*[[21 July]] – [[Cat Stevens]] (Steven Demetre Georgiou), singer-songwriter<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/743894.stm|title=Prince goes pop to praise school|date=10 May 2000|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=11 December 2012}}</ref> 
*[[2 August]] – [[Andy Fairweather Low]], guitarist, songwriter, producer and vocalist
*[[26 September]] – [[Olivia Newton-John]], singer and actress
*[[3 October]] – [[Ian MacDonald]] (Ian MacCormick), music critic (died [[2003 in British music|2003]])<ref>Williams, Richard. "[https://www.theguardian.com/obituaries/story/0,3604,1037260,00.html Obituary: Ian MacDonald]". The Guardian, 8 September 2003. Retrieved on 25 February 2008.</ref>
*[[11 October]] – [[David Rendall (tenor)|David Rendall]], operatic tenor
*[[3 November]] – [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]] (Marie McDonald McLaughlin Lawrie), singer and actress
*[[1 December]] – [[Colin Sell]], pianist
*[[20 December]] – [[Alan Parsons]], engineer and record producer

==Deaths==
*[[9 January]] – [[Violet Gordon-Woodhouse]], [[harpsichord]]ist and [[clavichord]]ist, 75<ref>{{cite book|author=Jessica Douglas-Home|title=Violet: The Life and Loves of Violet Gordon Woodhouse|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LogHAQAAMAAJ|year=1996|publisher=Harvill Press|isbn=978-1-86046-269-6}}</ref>
*[[21 February]] – [[Frederic Lamond (pianist)|Frederic Lamond]], pianist, 80
*[[17 May]] – [[David Evans (composer)|David Evans]], composer, 74<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s2-EVAN-DAV-1874.html |title=The National Library of Wales :: Dictionary of Welsh Biography |publisher=Wbo.llgc.org.uk |date=1948-05-17 |accessdate=2014-06-07}}</ref>
*[[14 June]] – [[John Blackwood McEwen]], composer, 80
*[[8 July]] – [[Reginald Somerville]], composer and actor, 81
*[[20 August]] – [[David John de Lloyd]], composer, 65
*[[12 September]] – [[Rupert D'Oyly Carte]], impresario, 70
*[[20 November]] – [[Robert Carr (baritone)|Robert Carr]], baritone, 67
*[[24 November]] – [[Nellie Wallace]], music hall star, actress, comedian, dancer and songwriter, 78<ref>{{citation |title=The Cambridge Guide to Theatre |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |year=2000 |chapter=Wallace, Nellie [Eleanor]}}</ref>
*[[14 December]] – [[R. O. Morris]], British composer and teacher, 62
*[[31 December]] – [[Ethel Barns]], violinist, pianist and composer, 74
*''date unknown'' – [[Euphemia Allen]], composer best known for "Chopsticks"

